{
  "texts": [
    "We have already observed the necessity of h being weakly conformal, so let us focus on suffiency.",
    "Let ǧ ∈ c be the hyperbolic metric and assume that h * g sym = νǧ for some function ν ≥ 0.",
    "Since h is ρ-equivariant and g sym is G-invariant, the pullback h * g sym is π 1 (B)-invariant.",
    "Thus, h * g sym is the pullback of a tensor on B 2 via the covering map.",
    "We will abuse notation and use the same symbol for the tensor on B 2 that pulls back to h * g sym.We must show that (20b) holds for some g B ∈ c. Any metric in g B ∈ c can be written as g B = e 2u ǧ for some u: B → R. The Gauss curvature of g B isK(g B) = e -2u (-∆ ḡ u -1).Hence, (20b) reduces to the scalar equation ( 24) ∆ ǧ u = 1 2 e 2u -1 -ν.To solve (24), consider the functional I: H 1 (B) → R defined byI[u] = B |du| 2 -u 1 + ν dvol ǧ.We minimise this subject to the Gauss-Bonnet constraint(25) 2πχ(B) + 1 2 B e 2u dvol ǧ = B ν dvol ǧObserve that the set of functions u: B → R satisfying ( 25) is non-empty since χ(B) < 0."
  ]
}